👉 Coupling = how much one class depends on another

Tight coupling → strongly dependent (hard to change) ❌
Loose coupling → less dependent (flexible, scalable) ✅

Let’s zoom in on the problem:
public class Tight.UserService {
    Tight.NotificationService notificationService = new Tight.NotificationService();
}

# Our code is Tightly coupled

🔥 Why this is Tight Coupling:
1. Direct object creation
- Tight.UserService itself creates Tight.NotificationService
- It is hardcoded
- No flexibility

2. What if tomorrow you want:
- EmailNotificationService?
- SMSNotificationService?
👉 You must modify Tight.UserService (bad)

3. Hard to test
You can’t easily mock or replace Tight.NotificationService


# How to Make It Loosely Coupled

We use abstraction + dependency injection

Step 1: Create Interface
public interface Tight.NotificationService {
    void send(String message);
}

Step 2: Implement It
public class EmailNotificationService implements Tight.NotificationService {
    public void send(String message){
        System.out.println("Email: " + message);
    }
}

Step 3: Inject Dependency
public class Tight.UserService {
    private Tight.NotificationService notificationService;

    public Tight.UserService(Tight.NotificationService notificationService){
        this.notificationService = notificationService;
    }

    public void notifyUser(String message) {
        notificationService.send(message);
    }
}

Step 4: Main Class
public class AppMain {
    public static void main(String[] args){
        Tight.NotificationService service = new EmailNotificationService();
        Tight.UserService userService = new Tight.UserService(service);

        userService.notifyUser("Order Placed!!");
    }
}

🔥 Now This is Loose Coupling
✅ Why this is better:

- You can switch easily:
new SmsNotificationService()
new PushNotificationService()
- No change in Tight.UserService ✔️
- Easy testing ✔️
- Scalable ✔️

*******************************************************************************************

💉 What is Dependency Injection (DI)?
👉 Dependency Injection = giving a class what it needs from outside instead of letting it create it itself

🧠 Break the word:
Dependency → something a class needs to work
Injection → providing it from outside

👉 So:

“Don’t create dependencies inside the class — inject them from outside.”

- Your Original Code (WITHOUT DI)
public class UserService {
    NotificationService notificationService = new NotificationService();
}
❌ Problem:
UserService is creating its dependency
This leads to tight coupling

✅ With Dependency Injection
public class UserService {
    private NotificationService notificationService;

    public UserService(NotificationService notificationService){
        this.notificationService = notificationService;
    }
}

✔️ What changed?
UserService is not creating
It is receiving the dependency

👉 That’s DI.

🔥 Types of Dependency Injection (Important)
1. Constructor Injection (Best ✅)
public UserService(NotificationService notificationService)
2. Setter Injection
public void setNotificationService(NotificationService ns)
3. Field Injection (used in Spring)
@Autowired
NotificationService notificationService;